<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>5 pricing tricks HVAC contractors use (and how to spot them)</title>
</head>
<body style="margin:0;padding:0;background-color:#ffffff;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;color:#27272a;">
  <div style="max-width:600px;margin:0 auto;padding:32px 20px;">

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Hey,</p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      Three days ago I sent you the 10-item checklist for evaluating your HVAC quotes. Today is the inside-baseball follow-up: the specific pricing tricks contractors use to make their bid look better than it is.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 24px 0;">
      None of these are illegal. Some are conscious cons; others are just industry habits the contractor isn't trying to hide. They all share one feature: the homeowner doesn't realize what's happening until after they've signed. Here are the five most common, with what to ask each contractor to surface them.
    </p>

    <!-- Trick 1 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 8px 0;">Trick #1 &mdash; The brand-substitution play</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>The pattern:</strong> the contractor quotes a known brand on the proposal (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.). On install day, they show up with a different brand or a lower-tier model from the same brand, with the explanation &ldquo;we're out of stock on that one &mdash; this one's equivalent.&rdquo; It usually isn't equivalent. The substitute is usually cheaper for them, while the price you pay stays the same.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>How to spot it:</strong> the quote names a brand and a tonnage but the model number is vague or missing. &ldquo;Carrier 16 SEER 3-ton&rdquo; is not a model. A real model number is alphanumeric and 8-12 characters long &mdash; like &ldquo;24ABB7&rdquo; or &ldquo;CSA624GKA.&rdquo; Vague description = wiggle room.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 8px 0;"><strong>How to counter:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Demand the full alphanumeric model number for both indoor and outdoor units on the written contract &mdash; and the AHRI certificate number (7 digits, looks like &ldquo;12345678&rdquo;). Cross-check it on ahridirectory.org before you sign. If they won't put a model number in writing, they don't actually know what they're installing.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Add a substitution clause: &ldquo;Any equipment substitution requires written notice 48 hours before install, with proof of equivalent AHRI certificate. Buyer reserves the right to cancel without penalty if the substitute differs in tonnage, SEER2/HSPF2, or refrigerant type.&rdquo; A real contractor signs this without flinching.</li>
      <li>On install day, before final payment, walk outside with the invoice and check the model number on the unit nameplate (usually a metal sticker on the side of the outdoor unit) against the contract. Two minutes of work; saves you the substitution every time.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Trick 2 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 8px 0;">Trick #2 &mdash; The labor-only quote (with hidden equipment markup)</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>The pattern:</strong> the contractor quotes labor at a low number, then orders equipment with significant markup over what you could buy it for at retail. The bottom-line price looks competitive, but you're overpaying on the equipment side. Counts on the homeowner not knowing what HVAC equipment actually costs.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>How to spot it:</strong> the quote shows labor and equipment as separate numbers, but the equipment line is significantly above retail. Some markup over retail is normal &mdash; the contractor handles ordering, delivery, returns, warranty registration. But the markup should be in the 15-25% range, not 60%.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 8px 0;"><strong>How to counter:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Spot-check the equipment cost on supplyhouse.com or HVACDirect. You don't need to price the whole job &mdash; pick the outdoor unit by model number and look up the wholesale price. Contractor markup of 15-25% over wholesale is normal; 50%+ is the trick.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Ask each contractor: &ldquo;Can you give me your hourly labor rate and the marked-up equipment subtotal as separate line items?&rdquo; The honest ones answer in one sentence. The trickier ones say &ldquo;we don't itemize that way&rdquo; &mdash; that itself is the answer.</li>
      <li>If two of your quotes have similar labor numbers but the equipment lines diverge by more than 20%, the higher-priced one is almost certainly running this play. Bring the wholesale price to the conversation: &ldquo;I see this unit retails for $X at SupplyHouse. Can you walk me through the markup?&rdquo;</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Trick 3 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 8px 0;">Trick #3 &mdash; The &ldquo;permit-by-homeowner&rdquo; dodge</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>The pattern:</strong> the contractor asks you to pull the permit. This shifts legal responsibility from the contractor to you. Sometimes there's a real reason (some jurisdictions allow owner-builder permits and the homeowner prefers it). More often it's a sign the contractor doesn't have the right license, isn't insured, or is trying to avoid the inspection paperwork.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>How to spot it:</strong> any quote where you're listed as the permit-puller, OR where the permit &ldquo;is included on your part&rdquo; or &ldquo;will be handled by the homeowner.&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 8px 0;"><strong>How to counter:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Refuse politely but firmly: &ldquo;I'd prefer my licensed contractor pull the permit, since you're the one doing the work.&rdquo; A legitimate contractor agrees in 10 seconds. One who pushes back is telling you why they don't want to.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">If they push back with &ldquo;it's faster this way&rdquo; or &ldquo;saves you a fee&rdquo; &mdash; those aren't reasons, they're hand-waves. Ask directly: &ldquo;Are you licensed for HVAC in this jurisdiction? What's your license number?&rdquo; Then verify it yourself.</li>
      <li>Look up the license online (every state has a free contractor license lookup &mdash; search &ldquo;[your state] contractor license search&rdquo;). Confirm: HVAC scope, current insurance on file, no open disciplinary actions. If the license doesn't check out, the cheapest install on your shortlist is no install at all.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Trick 4 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 8px 0;">Trick #4 &mdash; Under-scoped ductwork</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>The pattern:</strong> the quote is silent on ductwork. Mid-install, the contractor &ldquo;discovers&rdquo; issues &mdash; sealing, replacement runs, insulation upgrades &mdash; and adds $2-5K to the bill. By then you can't switch contractors without losing the partial install.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>How to spot it:</strong> the quote doesn't mention ductwork at all, or vaguely says &ldquo;ductwork as needed&rdquo; without specifying what was inspected.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 8px 0;"><strong>How to counter:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Get the duct inspection in writing &mdash; email, not verbal. Ask: &ldquo;Did you physically inspect the existing ductwork during the site visit? What's the condition? What duct work is in this quote, and what is explicitly excluded?&rdquo; A contractor who inspected can answer in three sentences. One who didn't will deflect.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Strike out any &ldquo;ductwork as needed&rdquo; line and replace it with itemized scope: &ldquo;Existing ducts inspected on [date]; condition: [acceptable / X linear feet of replacement needed / Y joints to be sealed]. Additional duct work, if discovered during install, charged at $X/linear foot or $Y/joint, requiring written approval.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>Add a contract clause capping mid-install change orders at 10% of the bid total without written approval, with your right to halt work if you disagree with the new scope. The contractor who refuses this clause is the one planning to use it against you.</li>
    </ul>

    {% if home.sqft >= 3000 %}
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;background-color:#fff7ed;border-left:3px solid #FF6B2B;padding:12px 16px;">
      At your home size ({{ home.sqft | comma }} sqft), this is one of the most common surprise charges. The clauses above are non-negotiable for a home this size.
    </p>
    {% endif %}

    <!-- Trick 5 -->
    <h3 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 8px 0;">Trick #5 &mdash; The &ldquo;we'll just do it in cash&rdquo; dodge</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>The pattern:</strong> the contractor offers a discount for cash payment, no contract, no permit. You save 10-15% on the headline number. They save much more &mdash; no taxes paid, no permit fees, no warranty obligations, no liability if something goes wrong.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>How to spot it:</strong> any cash discount that comes with &ldquo;we don't need to write everything down&rdquo; energy.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 8px 0;"><strong>How to counter:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 24px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Pay however you want, but always sign a written contract &mdash; with the brand, model, AHRI number, scope, warranty terms, and price. If the cash discount comes paired with &ldquo;we don't need to write this down,&rdquo; walk away. The contract is the warranty; without it, you have no warranty regardless of what they promised.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">Always require the permit to be pulled. The discount evaporates the first time something goes wrong &mdash; your homeowner's insurance can deny claims for unpermitted work, and so can your buyer's inspector when you sell the house in 5 years.</li>
      <li>If the cash discount is more than ~5%, the contractor isn't just dodging sales tax &mdash; they're likely uninsured for the install crew. If a tech falls off your roof, that's now your liability. Ask for proof of workers' comp + general liability insurance, in writing, with your address listed as the work site. A real contractor's insurer can issue a certificate same-day.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 8px 0;">If you spot any of these on your current quotes:</h3>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      The asymmetric move is getting one more independent bid. Honest contractors don't run these patterns. So if Quote A has the brand-substitution risk, Quote B has the labor-only structure, and you're trying to decide between them &mdash; you're choosing between two flavors of risk. A third bid from a contractor who passes the 10-item Day 0 checklist gives you a baseline you can actually trust.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      <a href="{{ cta_url }}" style="color:#FF6B2B;font-weight:600;text-decoration:underline;">Get one more independent quote &rarr;</a>
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 24px 0;">
      It takes 24 hours. If your existing quotes are clean, you've spent one phone call and learned that. If they're not, you've just saved yourself a problem.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 4px 0;">&mdash; NailTheQuote</p>
    <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;color:#71717a;font-style:italic;">
      P.S. On Day 10 &mdash; the final email &mdash; we'll cover how to actually choose between quotes once the bad ones are filtered out. The decision framework, the tiebreaker, and what to do when two quotes are within 5% on price.
    </p>

    {% include 'footer' %}

  </div>
</body>
</html>
